"``\n              \n              \nDIS 55\n&#xa0;\nThe Women’s Refugee Commission’s (WRC) \nseeks to advance the rights and dignity of persons with disabilities affected by crisis \nand conflict, \nthrough \nadvocacy, research and capacity development initiatives to\n \nsupport disability-inclusive refugee policy and practice at international and country l\nevels.\nThe WRC commends the UK Government \nDepartment for International Development (DFID) \nfor \nits commitment\n to persons with disabilities affected by crisis and conflict, most notably \nrecent support to \nSyrian refugees\n with disabilities in Jordan\n, as well a\ns wider commitments to advancing the \nConvention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities\n (CRPD) through support to partner governments and \ncapacity building \nfor\n \ndisabled\n people’s organizations (DPOs) in developing countries.\nRecommendations to the Intern\national Development Committee to further advance \ndisability inclusion across the wider humanitarian sector\n include:\n(i)&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n Expand understanding of ‘vulnerability’ in the humanitarian sector by supporting systematic \nreviews of available literature;\n conducting eva\nluations of prioritized and targeted assistance\n, identifying \nadvantages and disadvantages of different methodologies in \na variety of humanitarian\n contexts;\n and  promoting sharing and learning about these different methodologies\n across\n \nthe humanitarian sect\nor.\n&#xa0;\nContact:              Emma Pearce                            Senior Program Officer – Disability                            Women’s Refugee Commission                            Emmap@wrcommission.org&#xa0;\nDecember 2013              \nPage 7 \nWomen's Commission for Refugee Women and Children, \nDisabilities among refugees and conflict-affected populations\n (New York\n: Women's Refugee Commission, \n2008). \nhttp://wome\n